{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-js","path":"/mcd/","result":{"data":{"post":{"id":"ee8eb235-3c15-55b1-8fef-fdcbe295e73d","html":"<p>Eight years ago, my MacBook suffered a catastrophic hard drive failure.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/d43b4/laptop-in-fridge.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 85%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"A tweet about a laptop in a fridge\"\n        title=\"A tweet about a laptop in a fridge\"\n        src=\"/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/5a190/laptop-in-fridge.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/772e8/laptop-in-fridge.png 200w,\n/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/e17e5/laptop-in-fridge.png 400w,\n/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/5a190/laptop-in-fridge.png 800w,\n/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/c1b63/laptop-in-fridge.png 1200w,\n/static/1da09fdfc817c939ff3c184de8354cda/d43b4/laptop-in-fridge.png 1202w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Of course, I was no fool. I had everything backed up to our centralised backup system.\nBy horrible coincidence, that system also suffered a catastrophic failure the exact same week.\nI never got a full explanation of what happened but there was something about tapes and RAID arrays corrupting and everyone’s backup was lost.</p>\n<p>I was due to speak at JAX London the day after my laptop gave up the ghost, so I had a panicked twenty four hours trying to resuscitate my laptop while trying to recreate my demo while trying to make new slides.\nLuckily, it was the early days of mainstream-cloud, and\nI could just about fish my demo jar from of one cloud server, and an old PDF of my slides from another.\n(The demo code was lost forever, though, because it wasn’t on any public source control system.\nIt’s always surprising to me to look back at the recent past, ie 2014, and see how totally different it was from\nthe present I take for granted.)</p>\n<p>Once the initial crisis passed, it turns out losing everything was kind of liberating. I’d been\ncopying crud forward for thirteen year’s worth of laptops.\nOnce it was gone, I discovered almost none of it was actually necessary.</p>\n<p>But there was one thing I missed, and couldn’t get back – a one-line bash alias.\nIt was little, but it saved me effort every day.\nWhen I’d pair programmed, my buddies had commented admiringly on how useful it was.\nBut\nsometime between when I\nwrote the alias, and when my drive died, I’d lost most of my bash skills. That script haunted me. I kept trying to\nrecreate it – I mean, how hard can a one line bash alias be? – but without success.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/6568d/mcd-screencap.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 61%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"shell script showing mcd in action`\"\n        title=\"shell script showing mcd in action`\"\n        src=\"/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/5a190/mcd-screencap.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/772e8/mcd-screencap.png 200w,\n/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/e17e5/mcd-screencap.png 400w,\n/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/5a190/mcd-screencap.png 800w,\n/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/c1b63/mcd-screencap.png 1200w,\n/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/29007/mcd-screencap.png 1600w,\n/static/1172f31b5161871e8c91db05dc67cc39/6568d/mcd-screencap.png 1660w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Today, I recreated it. I don’t know if my implementation is as pure as my original, because I’ve had to rely on a function.\nBut that’s ok, because it’s just as <em>useful</em> as the original.</p>\n<p>What does this Proustian madeleine of shell scripting do? It makes a directory, and then puts you into that directory.\nIt’s such a common pattern, I don’t know why it’s not part of the core shell commands. (Ok, ok, I do know - the Unix\nphilosophy is to write small programs that do exactly one thing well, and can be chained together. Making a\ndirectory and then changing directory is two things. But still.)</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\">  holly@mac ~ % mcd awesome\n  holly@mac awesome % <span class=\"token builtin class-name\">pwd</span>\n  /Users/holly/awesome\n  holly@mac awesome %</code></pre></div>\n<p>Here’s the script, which I now have in my <code class=\"language-text\">.zprofile</code></p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\">    <span class=\"token function-name function\">mcd</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n     <span class=\"token function\">mkdir</span> <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-p</span> <span class=\"token variable\">$1</span> <span class=\"token operator\">&amp;&amp;</span> <span class=\"token builtin class-name\">cd</span> <span class=\"token variable\">$1</span>\n    <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>I hope this blog and <code class=\"language-text\">mcd</code> will be useful to someone else;\nbut if nothing else, I’ll know where to look for <code class=\"language-text\">mcd</code> next time my hard drive fails.</p>","excerpt":"Eight years ago, my MacBook suffered a catastrophic hard drive failure.  Of course, I was no fool. I had everything backed up to our…","fields":{"title":"mcd: the missing shell command","slug":"/mcd/","prefix":"2022-06-24","shortDate":"06-24","category":"unix","author":"Holly Cummins","displayCategory":"unix","geography":null,"video":null,"slides":null,"oembeds":null,"cover":{"childImageSharp":{"resize":{"src":"/static/46a392b11be9d5660a7098313f50c939/9dc27/mcd-comic.jpg"}}}},"frontmatter":{"type":"blog","event":null,"keynote":null,"code":null,"resources":null}},"authornote":{"id":"77e0dd69-1df1-59df-9a8e-f3f29c267627","html":"<p><strong>Holly Cummins</strong>. Holly Cummins is a Senior Principal Software Engineer at Red Hat, in the Quarkus Team. She is a\nkeynote speaker, author, and bad illustrator.</p>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/mcd/","prev":{"id":"d6cebf3f-8695-50ad-b892-7e58ea48353c","fields":{"slug":"/how-to-draw-part-ii/","prefix":"2022-06-17","draft":null,"source":"posts","category":"presentation-skills"},"frontmatter":{"title":"How to draw when you can’t draw, part ii: no really, how to draw","url":null,"type":"blog"}},"next":{